    <p class="text-gray-300">There is simple way to construct a distinguisher from an attacker <span class="math">(T,\\varepsilon)</span>-attacker <span class="math">\\mathbb{A}</span> against the McEliece cryptosystem. We denote it by <span class="math">\\mathcal{D}_{\\mathbb{A}}</span> and it works as follows. On a given input <span class="math">\\bm{G}</span>, it randomly picks a couple <span class="math">(\\bm{m},\\bm{e})</span> among <span class="math">\\mathbb{F}_{2}^{k}\\times\\mathcal{S}(\\bm{0},t)</span> and then outputs <span class="math">\\mathcal{D}_{\\mathbb{A}}(\\bm{G})=1</span> if <span class="math">\\mathbb{A}(\\bm{G},\\bm{m}\\bm{G}+\\bm{e})=(\\bm{m},\\bm{e})</span> and <span class="math">\\mathcal{D}_{\\mathbb{A}}(\\bm{G})=0</span> otherwise. The running time of <span class="math">\\mathcal{D}_{\\mathbb{A}}(\\bm{G})</span> is therefore uppe-bounded by the running time of <span class="math">\\mathbb{A}</span> and its advantage is then equal to <em>[28]</em>:</p>

