    <p class="text-gray-300">∎</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">This proposition shows that <span class="math">\\mathcal{B}_{r}</span> is a <span class="math">\\mathbb{F}_{q^{m}}</span>-basis that provides a <span class="math">\\mathbb{F}_{q}</span>-basis of <span class="math">\\mathrm{Ker}(\\mathcal{L}_{\\bm{P}})</span> allowing us to suggest an heuristic: consider an arbitrary decomposition of the elements of <span class="math">\\mathbb{F}_{q^{m}}</span> in a <span class="math">\\mathbb{F}_{q}</span> basis. Let <span class="math">\\pi_{i}:\\mathbb{F}_{q^{m}}\\to\\mathbb{F}_{q}</span> be the function giving the <span class="math">i</span>-th coordinate in this decomposition with <span class="math">1\\leqslant i\\leqslant m</span>. By extension we denote for <span class="math">\\bm{z}=(z_{j})_{1\\leqslant j\\leqslant n}\\in(\\mathbb{F}_{q^{m}})^{n}</span> by <span class="math">\\pi_{i}(\\bm{z})</span> the vector <span class="math">(\\pi_{i}(z_{j}))_{1\\leqslant j\\leqslant n}\\in\\mathbb{F}_{q}^{n}</span>.</p>

