    <p class="text-gray-300">where <span class="math">K</span> is the constant appearing in Lemma 4.</p>

    <h6 id="sec-39" class="text-base font-medium mt-4">Proof:</h6>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Let <span class="math">D\\stackrel{{\\scriptstyle\\rm def}}{{=}}\\sum_{i=1}^{t}d(\\bm{M}_{i})</span>. Using Markov’s inequality:</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">\\mathbf{Pr}(D\\geqslant u)\\leqslant\\frac{\\mathbb{E}(q^{\\lambda D})}{q^{\\lambda u}}</span> (20)</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">for some well chosen <span class="math">\\lambda&gt;0</span>. The exponential moment appearing at the numerator is upper-bounded with the help of the previous lemma and by using the independence of the random variables <span class="math">q^{\\lambda d(\\bm{M}_{i})}</span> <em>i.e.</em>:</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">\\mathbb{E}(q^{\\lambda D})</span> <span class="math">=</span> <span class="math">\\mathbb{E}\\left(q^{\\lambda\\sum_{i=1}^{t}d(M_{i})}\\right)=\\prod_{i=1}^{t}\\mathbb{E}\\left(q^{\\lambda d(\\bm{M}_{i})}\\right)</span> (21) <span class="math">\\leqslant</span> <span class="math">K^{t}q^{\\frac{i\\lambda^{2}}{4}}.</span></p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Using now (21) in (20), we obtain <span class="math">\\mathbf{Pr}(D\\geqslant\\alpha t)\\leqslant K^{t}\\frac{q^{\\frac{i\\lambda^{2}}{4}}}{q^{\\lambda u}}</span> which implies:</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">\\mathbf{Pr}(D\\geqslant\\alpha t)\\leqslant K^{t}q^{\\frac{i\\lambda^{2}}{4}-\\lambda u}.</span></p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">We choose <span class="math">\\lambda=\\frac{2n}{t}</span> to minimize this upper-bound leading to:</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">\\mathbf{Pr}(D\\geqslant u)\\leqslant K^{t}q^{-\\frac{u^{2}}{t}}.</span></p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">The last ingredient for proving Theorem 2 is a bound on the probability that <span class="math">E_{i}</span> is too small to construct <span class="math">F_{i}</span>.</p>

